{{was wotd|2007|May|13}}

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|īnflectō}}, from {{m|la|in-||in}} + {{m|la|flectō||I bend}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ɪnˈflɛkt/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-inflect.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-inflect.ogg|Audio (AU)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɛkt}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause to [[curve]] inwards.
# {{lb|en|transitive|music}} To change the [[tone]] or [[pitch]] of the voice when speaking or singing.
#: {{ux|en|The actress has a great skill of being able to '''inflect''' her voice to any situation.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|grammar}} To vary the form of a [[word]] to express [[tense]], [[gender]], [[number]], [[mood]], etc.
# {{lb|en|transitive|grammar|of a word}} To be varied in the form to express [[tense]], [[gender]], [[number]], [[mood]], etc.
#: {{ux|en|In Latin, adjectives and nouns '''inflect''' a lot, but inflection is minimally found in Modern English.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[influence]] in [[style]].
#: {{ux|en|No other poet has '''inflected''' me in style as much as Milton.}}

